  "doc_id": "6717",
  "text": "Cesium is known to block a number of K+ channels [CITATION_1] , and can increase spike duration by reducing the delayedrectifier current [CITATION_2] Puil and Werman, 198 1) . This effect in the present study verified the effectiveness of intrapipette Cs+. Thus, the suppression of spontaneous, long-lasting hyperpolarizations in the presence of Cs+ can be attributed to blockade of K+ channels. Since both Cs+ and NB stimulation reduced long-lasting hyperpolarizations, and since NB stimulation was no longer effective following complete Cs+ effects, we suggest a convergence of Cs+ and NB actions at K+ channels. It is unlikely, however, that Cs+ and NB actions overlap completely, since (1) NB stimulation never increased spike duration in K+-based solutions, and (2) many K+ channels sensitive to blockade by Cs+, including the delayed rectifier [CITATION_3] are not affected by muscarinic actions of ACh. Thus, Cs+ and NB actions may overlap at the K+ current underlying the spontaneous, long-lasting hyperpolarization; this current is unlikely to be the delayed rectifier.",
